<HEADLINE>
<P>
PROSECUTORS ASK COURT TO TRANSFER FRAUD DEFENDANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. Magistrate Ronald W. Rose said Monday that he will consider a request by 
federal prosecutors to transfer Capistrano Beach resident Douglas P. 
Blankenship to a prison in Tacoma, Wash., while he awaits trial on charges that 
he conspired to defraud financial institutions in seven states of $25 million. 
</P>
<P>
The U.S. attorney's office in Tacoma, headquarters for the alleged scheme's 
largest victim, is trying the case against Blankenship. 
</P>
<P>
Rose scheduled a a hearing for Nov. 29 on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
The magistrate also denied a second bail request by former Huntington Beach 
resident Michael E. Hilander, one of 14 co-defendants with Blankenship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
