<HEADLINE>
<P>
POLAND PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE IS ASSAILED; 
</P>
<P>
POLITICS: "WE ARE BEGINNING TO SEE THE FIGURE OF AN INSANE PERSON," A NEWSPAPER 
SAYS OF STANISLAW TYMINSKI. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WARSAW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An emigre businessman who soared into contention in Poland's presidential race 
struggled today to keep his campaign afloat as the government threatened him 
with prosecution and newspapers called him a madman and a fraud. 
</P>
<P>
Stanislaw Tyminski defiantly repeated his accusation that Prime Minister 
Tadeusz Mazowiecki had betrayed the country by selling Poland's best companies 
to foreigners at bargain-basement prices. 
</P>
<P>
But Tyminski, who made a $5-million fortune in Canada and Peru, has been 
attacked by opponents who question his business record, campaign promises and 
even his sanity. 
</P>
<P>
"From what he says and how he says it, we are beginning to see the figure of an 
insane person, with a mixture of megalomania and a dangerous, though grotesque, 
persecution complex," the pro-Mazowiecki newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza said. 
</P>
<P>
Tyminski, whose vision to free Poland from economic slavery has caught the 
imagination of many voters, has thrown the presidential election campaign into 
turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
Unknown a month ago, he soared in the opinion polls to within striking distance 
of Mazowiecki and threatened to snatch second place in Sunday's first ballot 
behind Solidarity leader Lech Walesa. 
</P>
<P>
But Tyminski failed at a news conference to substantiate his allegations 
against Mazowiecki, which prompted prosecutors on Monday to start investigating 
him for slander. 
</P>
<P>
With five days left before the vote, it was unclear whether the attacks against 
him would destroy Tyminski's campaign or win even more people to vote for him 
out of sympathy. 
</P>
<P>
Though short on charisma, the quiet, bespectacled Tyminski has impressed many 
with his apparent business acumen and almost prophetic vision of future 
prosperity for Poland. 
</P>
<P>
Tyminski calls the Solidarity government's austerity policies "a mechanism of 
enslavement of our country." He tells audiences across the country that Poland 
is a victim of international economic warfare that threatens to make it a 
nation of "white slaves." 
</P>
<P>
Voters applaud enthusiastically as Tyminski tells them Poles could make 
billions of dollars if freed from an oppressive tax system that throttles 
initiative and success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Stanislaw Tyminski Reuters 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
