</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BEIJING 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Volkswagen AG and China's First Automobile Works signed an $807-million joint 
venture agreement today, pledging to produce 150,000 locally made Golf cars by 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
China welcomed the deal as a "major project" in its new economic blueprint. 
</P>
<P>
Work on the new venture between the giant German auto maker and China's oldest 
auto company is slated to begin next year in the city of Changchun, in 
northeast Jilin province. 
</P>
<P>
Volkswagen Chairman Carl Hahn and his Chinese counterpart were optimistic but 
vague about the venture's ambitious goals. Neither side would give the 
estimated price of the Chinese-made Golfs. Hahn said only that the cars would 
cost less than Shanghai-produced VW Santanas, which sell for $27,000. 
</P>
